{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528585"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:45:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:45:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14317"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14317"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.04,0.15,0.52,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108807"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7012"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91170"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"2981"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38182"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108807"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of increasing left upper quadrant pain. The pain is constant in nature and worse when he breathes in deeply. He has also noticed some discomfort over his left shoulder. His medical history is unremarkable apart from an episode of pancreatitis three months ago. This was thought to be gallstone-related and a cholecystectomy was performed. He does not take any regular medications. He is an ex-smoker and drinks about four glasses of wine at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 118/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. There is some tenderness in the left upper quadrant on palpation. The rest of the abdominal examination is unremarkable. Chest auscultation reveals normal breath sounds bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatic pseudocyst","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Splenic haematoma","Subphrenic abscess","Splenomegaly"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a large collection under the left hemidiaphragm with visible locules of gas within it (Image). This appearance, together with the clinical picture of diaphragmatic irritation (left shoulder pain) and fever, supports the diagnosis of a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubphrenic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E. It is likely that the patient had a pseudocyst formed after the episode of pancreatitis, which has become infected. Subphrenic abscesses can be a complication of abdominal surgeries or conditions like pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic pseudocyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility given the patient\u0027s history of pancreatitis. However, pseudocysts typically do not contain gas and are not usually associated with fever unless infected. The presence of gas and fever makes a subphrenic abscess more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal stromal tumour (GIST)\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare type of tumour that can occur anywhere in the gastrointestinal tract. While it can present with abdominal pain, it typically does not cause fever or contain gas. GISTs usually appear as solid masses on CT, not fluid-filled collections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause left upper quadrant pain, but it would not explain the fever or the gas-containing collection seen on CT. Splenic haematomas are typically associated with trauma, which is not mentioned in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenomegaly\u003C/strong\u003E refers to an enlarged spleen, which can cause left upper quadrant discomfort. However, it would not explain the fever or the gas-containing collection seen on the CT scan. Splenomegaly would appear as a uniformly enlarged spleen on imaging, not a loculated collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of a subphrenic abscess best fits this clinical picture. The patient\u0027s history of recent abdominal surgery (cholecystectomy) and pancreatitis are risk factors for developing such an abscess. The presentation of upper quadrant pain, fever, and referred shoulder pain (due to diaphragmatic irritation) is classic for this condition. CT scan is the gold standard for diagnosing subphrenic abscesses, typically showing a collection with gas locules under the diaphragm, as seen in this case. Treatment usually involves percutaneous drainage under CT guidance, along with appropriate antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subphrenic abscesses often present with upper quadrant pain, fever, and referred shoulder pain due to diaphragmatic irritation.","CT scan is the gold standard for diagnosing subphrenic abscesses, typically showing a collection with gas locules under the diaphragm.","Subphrenic abscesses can be a complication of abdominal surgeries or conditions like pancreatitis."],"references":["Thompson DT, Hrabe JE. Intra-abdominal and Anorectal Abscesses. Gastroenterol Clin N Am 2021; 50:475\u201388"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91170"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14317"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21077"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21947"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21077"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4N9nXvGH14UQvXlYisBSiyvGpLH1MX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4N9nXvGH14UQvXlYisBSiyvGpLH1MX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":844,"height":624}},{"type":"media","id":"21947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21947"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tiueL1BDXwmUImPjsrOM1C91mxxOZC.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tiueL1BDXwmUImPjsrOM1C91mxxOZC.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":844,"height":624}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91170"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T15:13:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T15:14:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7012"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108807"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09